e 'Wimp' Stokes's funeral legendary]</span>. Ottawa Citizen. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CTLBG\">Greene, Bob (September 2, 1990). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-09-02/features/9003130830_1_stevie-ray-vaughan-cadillac-coffin-fitting-tribute Thanks, Stevie, For Playing Our Song]</span>. ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"dcdc\">[http://www.discogs.com/Bill-Carter-Stompin-Grounds/release/2565478 Bill Carter ''Stompin Grounds'']. discogs.com. Retrieved October 28, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ALMLA\">(July 1986). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-alive-mw0000192201 ''Live Alive'']</span>. Allmusic.com. Retrieved May 31, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CTNKIA\">Wattley, Philip; Sullivan, Paul; O'Brien, John; Baumann, Edward (November 19, 1986). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-11-19/news/8603270121_1_portable-trafficking-willie-flukey-stokes Drug King Stokes Killed In Ambush]</span>. ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CTNbw2\">Baumann, Edward; O'Brien, John; Sullivan, Paul; Wattley, Philip; Myers, Linnet (November 19, 1986). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-11-19/news/8603260988_1_flukey-stokes-drug-dealer-bottled-water/2 Reputed Drug King Killed In Ambush (Page 2 of 2)]</span>. ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARLFH\">(November 19, 1986). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1345&dat=19861119&id=d7cSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=x_kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4555,658476 Flashy funeral is certain for drug kingpin]</span>. ''Spokane Chronicle''. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CTN7K\">Brotman, Barbara (November 22, 1986). <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-11-22/news/8603270875_1_coffin-willie-flukey-stokes-portable 7,000 Say Farewell To Flukey]</span>. ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved May 30, 2013.</ref>\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Tucker, Donald W. (July 19, 2010). ''The Two-Edged Sword''. Indianapolis, IN: Dog Ear Publishing. {{ISBN|9781608445660}}.\n* Deparle, Jason (August 30, 2005). ''American Dream: Three Women, Ten Kids, And A Nation's Drive to End Welfare''.  New York, NY: Viking Penguin. {{ISBN|9781448713073}}.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stokes, Willie}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American mobsters]]\n[[Category:American mobsters]]\n[[Category:American mob bosses]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Chicago]]\n[[Category:Murdered American mobsters]]\n[[Category:Murdered mobsters]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSounds like a song:Typo fixing, replaced: songs lyrics \u2192 song's lyrics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flukey_Stokes"}
{"title_page": "Alladale Wilderness Reserve", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Alladale Wilderness Reserve\n| alt_name =\n\n| photo = West of Alladale Lodge - geograph.org.uk - 629647.jpg\n| photo_width = 240\n| photo_caption = <small> Glen Alladale</small>\n| photo_alt =\n\n| map = Scotland Sutherland\n| map_width = 240\n| map_caption = <small>[[File:Red pog.svg|8px]]&nbsp;Alladale Wilderness Reserve shown within [[Sutherland]]</small>\n| map_alt = \n| map_label = Alladale Wilderness Reserve\n| map_label_position = right \n| relief = \n| mark =\n\n| grid_ref_UK = NH439897\n| coords =  {{coord|57.8697|N|4.6333|W|region:GB|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref =\n\n| type = \n| location = \n| nearest_city = \n| area = {{convert|23000|acre|km2}}\n| elevation = \n| created = \n| designer = \n| etymology = \n| operator = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref = \n| status = \n| awards = \n| open = \n| camp_sites = \n| hiking_trails = \n| other_info = \n| website = {{URL|www.alladale.co.uk}}\n\n|child = \n|embedded = \n}}\n\n'''Alladale Wilderness Reserve''' is a privately owned reserve in the [[Caledonian Forest]] in [[Sutherland]], in the [[Scottish Highlands]]. It is being managed so as to restore it to its natural state by increasing the tree cover of the glen, reintroducing native animals which are no longer found in [[Great Britain]] and encouraging [[biodiversity]]. Alladale Wilderness Reserve is currently the United Kingdom's largest [[Rewilding (conservation biology)|wilderness engineering]] and [[rewilding (conservation biology)|rewilding]] area.\n\n==Environmental degradation  and biodiversity losses in the British Isles==\n7,000 years ago, Britain was heavily forested. It would have been populated with wolves, bears, lynx, elk and a myriad of other large animals [https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/history_of_the_earth/Holocene]. But humans began to cut down a lot of the native forest, to make room for farmland. Almost all the large mammals had been forced into extinction by various means. Wolves were the last to go, becoming extinct in Scotland and Ireland in the 17th and 18th centuries respectively. Britain 7,000 years ago probably would have looked more like the untamed wilderness of [[Alaska]], than the criss-cross of farmland seen today. The remotest highlands of Scotland prove to be the best candidates for [[rewilding (conservation biology)|rewilding]] in Britain.\n\n==Background==\nThe Alladale estate was bought by English multimillionaire Paul Lister in 2003. The idea of a wilderness reserve was inspired by visits to [[South Africa|South Africa's]] ever popular [[game reserve]]s.   \nThe idea was to create an area of outstanding natural beauty, where animals previously extinct in Britain could be reintroduced. Letting nature return itself to an early [[Holocene]] setting by bringing in the right animals. This idea has been proven in South Africa, when over-grazed down graded farmland, was returned to its natural setting.\n\nArguably the most important aspect of the reserve are the predators. As deer are already common in the park, they over graze the land, and trample any saplings (impeding another important aspect, the regeneration of the rare Caledonian forest). This (in theory) should be a more effective way of balancing the deer population, than culling, which so far has poor results. Another positive aspect of reintroducing large predators is the increase in tourism (see [[Yellowstone National Park]]).\n\n==Wilderness reserve==\nThe reserve is part of Glen Alladale, a broad glacial valley surrounded by {{convert|2300|ft|adj=on}} mountains in a remote area near [[Ardgay]] in [[Sutherland]]. The Alladale estate of {{convert|23000|acre}} was purchased in 2003 by Paul Lister, an English philanthropist, who hopes to recreate a natural wooded landscape and reintroduce native animals including [[Predation|predators]] such as the [[Eurasian wolf|wolf]] and [[Eurasian brown bear|bear]]. The natural flora of the area consists of [[Scots pine]], [[oak]], [[aspen]], [[birch]], [[rowan]], [[holly]], [[willow]] and [[juniper]], but much of the tree cover has been lost and low heathers, grasses and sedges now predominate. In 2014, about 800,000 saplings of these native trees have been planted. A feasibility study to investigate the potential effects of a controlled release of wolves and bears into the area is planned for 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Scotland\u2019s Search for Roots, A Push to Restore Wild Lands |author=Caroline Fraser |url=http://e360.yale.edu/feature/in_scotlands_search_for_roots_a_push_to_restore_wild_lands/2319/ |newspaper=Yale Environment 360 |date=2010-09-16 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe estate is an access route to the hill known as [[C\u00e0rn Ban]], which is a [[List of Marilyns in the Northern Highlands|Corbett]] in the [[Seana Bhr\u00e0igh]] mountain range.<ref name=\"Walkhighlands\">{{cite web | title=Carn Ban (Walkhighlands) | website=Walkhighlands | url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/corbetts/carn-ban | accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Fauna==\nWild animals found living in the reserve include [[red deer]], [[roe deer]], [[European otter|otter]], [[red fox]], [[mountain hare]], [[European badger|badger]], [[European pine marten|pine marten]] and Britain's most threatened mammal, the [[European water vole|water vole]]. [[Brown trout]] and [[Atlantic salmon|salmon]] are found in the rivers and streams. The moors are clad in [[Calluna|ling]] and [[Erica cinerea|bell heather]] and are home to [[black grouse]], [[red grouse]] and [[Rock ptarmigan|ptarmigan]]. Other large birds found in the reserve include the [[golden eagle]], [[white-tailed eagle]], [[osprey]], [[Common buzzard|buzzard]], [[peregrine falcon]], [[merlin (bird)|merlin]], [[Common kestrel|kestrel]] and [[Common raven|raven]].<ref name=Alladale>{{cite web |url=http://www.alladale.co.uk/ |title=Alladale Wilderness Reserve |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nRed deer are the most common large mammal on the reserve. Their grazing has thwarted many previous attempts to restore the Caledonian forest. Deer stalking has proved effective at controlling their numbers. Wolves and lynx, may however prove a cheaper, easier, better, and more natural alternative to the deer problem. It is probably the deprivation of natural predators that drove deer numbers over the edge.\n[[File:Silz cerf8.jpg|thumbnail|Red deer numbers increase rapidly and therefore need to be controlled.]]\n\nThe European Nature Trust (TENT), is a charitable organisation founded by Paul Lister which focuses on the protection of threatened wilderness area. It has provided funds for the planting of native trees in the Kyle of Sutherland catchment area. This includes over 940,000 trees which had been planted at the start of 2020 on the Alladale Wilderness Reserve. TENT considers that forest restoration is important \"for many reasons, including supporting some of the UK\u2019s rarest species, helping to reduce pollution, generate oxygen, enrich the biodiversity of river tributaries, improving spawning and feeding grounds for native fish, providing natural barriers from flooding and filters for clean water.\" Another TENT project at the reserve involves planting trees with edible fruits to provide food for wildlife. These include [[Malus|wild apple]], [[hazel]], [[Crataegus monogyna|hawthorn]] and [[Quercus petraea|sessile oak]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theeuropeannaturetrust.com/en/scottishforestry/ |title=Scottish Forestry Restoration |author=Innes MacNeill, Alan Ross |publisher=European Nature Trust |accessdate=2013-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624092951/http://www.theeuropeannaturetrust.com/en/scottishforestry/ |archive-date=2013-06-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism== \n[[Walking in the United Kingdom|Ramblers and hillwalkers]] are concerned that the fence will prevent access to grounds within the reserve. Enclosure would contravene principles of open access enshrined in the [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003]] unless stiles and gates were provided. Whilst the [[Ramblers]] support reintroductions, they see charging for access to fenced enclosures as a way for owners of large estates to subvert the Act.<ref name=\"Weymouth 2015\">{{cite web | last=Weymouth | first=Adam | title=The place where wolves could soon return | website=BBC News | date=14 October 2015 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-33017511 | accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Animals for reintroduction==\nThe following animals have been, or are being, considered for reintroduction:\n\n===Herbivores===\n*[[Horse]] - several highland ponies live on the reserve, as a proxy for the extinct [[tarpan]].\n*[[Bovinae|Bovine]] - [[Highland cattle]] can be found living wild, as a proxy for the extinct [[aurochs]].\n*[[Wild boar]] - can be found roaming around the woodland of the reserve.\n\n===Predators===\n*[[Gray wolf|Wolf]] - it was intended for a pack of four wolves to be released, but plans have been postponed.  \n*[[Bear]] - an omnivorous animal, that can hibernate throughout the harsh winter.\n*[[Lynx]] - necessary for controlling the numbers of the small roe deer.\n*[[Wildcat]] - three wildcats are currently housed in an enclosure on the estate.\n[[File:LOUP d'EUROPE 0060.jpg|thumbnail|A wolf, one of the most controversial aspects of Alladale]]\n\n==Visiting the reserve==\nThere is a lodge accompanied by two cottages on the reserve offering accommodation and various activities are available including [[hiking]], [[deer stalking]], [[Skeet shooting|clay pigeon shooting]], [[angling]], [[mountain biking]] and [[safari]]s using off-road vehicles. There is also a programme for groups of youngsters known as the \"Highland Outdoors Wilderness Learning programme (HOWL)\" in which they participate in adventurous activities and sleep in tents. This programme for local school children was set up by the Challenger Trust as an offshoot of the popular World Challenge series of programmes. Funding was originally shared with the National Lottery but with the expiration of that source the European Nature Trust (TENT) has continued to fund it in collaboration with Highland Birchwoods. TENT would welcome any contributions either to fund or develop the programme.<ref name=Alladale/>\n\nThe British adventurer and television presenter [[Bear Grylls]] has set up the Bear Grylls Survival Academy here. Participants learn such skills as [[self-sufficiency]], [[Animal trapping|trapping]] wild animals, fire lighting, building emergency shelters and [[Hand-to-hand combat|unarmed combat]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bear Grylls Survival Academy: roasted rat for dinner, anyone? |author=Oliver Smith |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/9698850/Bear-Grylls-Survival-Academy-roasted-rat-for-dinner-anyone.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2012-11-23 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nAs with all land in Scotland, there is a [[freedom to roam|right of responsible access]] to the reserve for pursuits such as [[hiking|walking]], [[cycling]], [[horse-riding]] and [[wild camping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.scot/sites/default/files/2018-05/Publication%202005%20-%20Scottish%20Outdoor%20Access%20Code.pdf|title=Scottish Outdoor Access Code|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date= 2005|accessdate=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rewilding]]\n[[Category:Wilderness areas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Alladale Wilderness Reserve\n| alt_name =\n\n| photo = West of Alladale Lodge - geograph.org.uk - 629647.jpg\n| photo_width = 240\n| photo_caption = <small> Glen Alladale</small>\n| photo_alt =\n\n| map = Scotland Sutherland\n| map_width = 240\n| map_caption = <small>[[File:Red pog.svg|8px]]&nbsp;Alladale Wilderness Reserve shown within [[Sutherland]]</small>\n| map_alt = \n| map_label = Alladale Wilderness Reserve\n| map_label_position = right \n| relief = \n| mark =\n\n| grid_ref_UK = NH439897\n| coords =  {{coord|57.8697|N|4.6333|W|region:GB|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref =\n\n| type = \n| location = \n| nearest_city = \n| area = {{convert|23000|acre|km2}}\n| elevation = \n| created = \n| designer = \n| etymology = \n| operator = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref = \n| status = \n| awards = \n| open = \n| camp_sites = \n| hiking_trails = \n| other_info = \n| website = {{URL|www.alladale.co.uk}}\n\n|child = \n|embedded = \n}}\n\n'''Alladale Wilderness Reserve''' is a privately owned estate in the [[Caledonian Forest]] in [[Sutherland]], in the [[Scottish Highlands]]. It is being managed so as to restore it to its natural state by increasing the tree cover of the glen, reintroducing native animals which are no longer found in [[Great Britain]] and encouraging [[biodiversity]]. Alladale Wilderness Reserve is currently the United Kingdom's largest [[Rewilding (conservation biology)|wilderness engineering]] and [[rewilding (conservation biology)|rewilding]] area.\n\n==Environmental degradation  and biodiversity losses in the British Isles==\n7,000 years ago, Britain was heavily forested. It would have been populated with wolves, bears, lynx, elk and a myriad of other large animals [https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/history_of_the_earth/Holocene]. But humans began to cut down a lot of the native forest, to make room for farmland. Almost all the large mammals had been forced into extinction by various means. Wolves were the last to go, becoming extinct in Scotland and Ireland in the 17th and 18th centuries respectively. Britain 7,000 years ago probably would have looked more like the untamed wilderness of [[Alaska]], than the criss-cross of farmland seen today. The remotest highlands of Scotland prove to be the best candidates for [[r