lves and bears into the area is planned for 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Scotland\u2019s Search for Roots, A Push to Restore Wild Lands |author=Caroline Fraser |url=http://e360.yale.edu/feature/in_scotlands_search_for_roots_a_push_to_restore_wild_lands/2319/ |newspaper=Yale Environment 360 |date=2010-09-16 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe estate is an access route to the hill known as [[C\u00e0rn Ban]], which is a [[List of Marilyns in the Northern Highlands|Corbett]] in the [[Seana Bhr\u00e0igh]] mountain range.<ref name=\"Walkhighlands\">{{cite web | title=Carn Ban (Walkhighlands) | website=Walkhighlands | url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/corbetts/carn-ban | accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Fauna==\nWild animals found living in the reserve include [[red deer]], [[roe deer]], [[European otter|otter]], [[red fox]], [[mountain hare]], [[European badger|badger]], [[European pine marten|pine marten]] and Britain's most threatened mammal, the [[European water vole|water vole]]. [[Brown trout]] and [[Atlantic salmon|salmon]] are found in the rivers and streams. The moors are clad in [[Calluna|ling]] and [[Erica cinerea|bell heather]] and are home to [[black grouse]], [[red grouse]] and [[Rock ptarmigan|ptarmigan]]. Other large birds found in the reserve include the [[golden eagle]], [[white-tailed eagle]], [[osprey]], [[Common buzzard|buzzard]], [[peregrine falcon]], [[merlin (bird)|merlin]], [[Common kestrel|kestrel]] and [[Common raven|raven]].<ref name=Alladale>{{cite web |url=http://www.alladale.co.uk/ |title=Alladale Wilderness Reserve |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nRed deer are the most common large mammal on the reserve. Their grazing has thwarted many previous attempts to restore the Caledonian forest. Deer stalking has proved effective at controlling their numbers. Wolves and lynx, may however prove a cheaper, easier, better, and more natural alternative to the deer problem. It is probably the deprivation of natural predators that drove deer numbers over the edge.\n[[File:Silz cerf8.jpg|thumbnail|Red deer numbers increase rapidly and therefore need to be controlled.]]\n\nThe European Nature Trust (TENT), is a charitable organisation founded by Paul Lister which focuses on the protection of threatened wilderness area. It has provided funds for the planting of native trees in the Kyle of Sutherland catchment area. This includes over 800,000 trees which had been planted by the end of 2014 on the Alladale Wilderness Reserve. TENT considers that forest restoration is important \"for many reasons, including supporting some of the UK\u2019s rarest species, helping to reduce pollution, generate oxygen, enrich the biodiversity of river tributaries, improving spawning and feeding grounds for native fish, providing natural barriers from flooding and filters for clean water.\" Another TENT project at the reserve involves planting trees with edible fruits to provide food for wildlife. These include [[Malus|wild apple]], [[hazel]], [[Crataegus monogyna|hawthorn]] and [[Quercus petraea|sessile oak]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theeuropeannaturetrust.com/en/scottishforestry/ |title=Scottish Forestry Restoration |author=Innes MacNeill, Alan Ross |publisher=European Nature Trust |accessdate=2013-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624092951/http://www.theeuropeannaturetrust.com/en/scottishforestry/ |archive-date=2013-06-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism== \n[[Walking in the United Kingdom|Ramblers and hillwalkers]] are concerned that the fence will prevent access to grounds within the reserve. Enclosure would contravene principles of open access enshrined in the [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003]] unless stiles and gates were provided. Whilst the [[Ramblers]] support reintroductions, they see charging for access to fenced enclosures as a way for owners of large estates to subvert the Act.<ref name=\"Weymouth 2015\">{{cite web | last=Weymouth | first=Adam | title=The place where wolves could soon return | website=BBC News | date=14 October 2015 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-33017511 | accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Animals for reintroduction==\nThe following animals have been, or are being, considered for reintroduction:\n\n===Herbivores===\n*[[Horse]] - several highland ponies live on the reserve, as a proxy for the extinct [[tarpan]].\n*[[Bovinae|Bovine]] - [[Highland cattle]] can be found living wild, as a proxy for the extinct [[aurochs]].\n*[[Wild boar]] - can be found roaming around the woodland of the reserve.\n\n===Predators===\n*[[Gray wolf|Wolf]] - it was intended for a pack of four wolves to be released, but plans have been postponed.  \n*[[Bear]] - an omnivorous animal, that can hibernate throughout the harsh winter.\n*[[Lynx]] - necessary for controlling the numbers of the small roe deer.\n*[[Wildcat]] - three wildcats are currently housed in an enclosure on the estate.\n[[File:LOUP d'EUROPE 0060.jpg|thumbnail|A wolf, one of the most controversial aspects of Alladale]]\n\n==Visiting the reserve==\nThere is a lodge accompanied by two cottages on the estate offering accommodation and various activities are available including [[hiking]], [[deer stalking]], [[Skeet shooting|clay pigeon shooting]], [[angling]], [[mountain biking]] and [[safari]]s using off-road vehicles. There is also a programme for groups of youngsters known as the \"Alladale School's Challenge\" in which they participate in adventurous activities and sleep in tents. This programme for local school children was set up by the Challenger Trust as an offshoot of the popular World Challenge series of programmes. Funding was originally shared with the National Lottery but with the expiration of that source the European Nature Trust (TENT) has continued to fund it in collaboration with Highland Birchwoods. TENT would welcome any contributions either to fund or develop the programme.<ref name=Alladale/>\n\nThe British adventurer and television presenter [[Bear Grylls]] has set up the Bear Grylls Survival Academy here. Participants learn such skills as [[self-sufficiency]], [[Animal trapping|trapping]] wild animals, fire lighting, building emergency shelters and [[Hand-to-hand combat|unarmed combat]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bear Grylls Survival Academy: roasted rat for dinner, anyone? |author=Oliver Smith |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/9698850/Bear-Grylls-Survival-Academy-roasted-rat-for-dinner-anyone.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2012-11-23 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nAs with all land in Scotland, there is a [[freedom to roam|right of responsible access]] to the estate for pursuits such as [[hiking|walking]], [[cycling]], [[horse-riding]] and [[wild camping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.scot/sites/default/files/2018-05/Publication%202005%20-%20Scottish%20Outdoor%20Access%20Code.pdf|title=Scottish Outdoor Access Code|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date= 2005|accessdate=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rewilding]]\n[[Category:Wilderness areas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Pieter-Paul G", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed some wording (estate vs. reserve), updated the number of trees planted, and updated the name of the local school's programme to HOWL.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alladale_Wilderness_Reserve"}
{"title_page": "Tung Chung line", "text_new": "{{short description|Hong Kong railway line}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name    = {{HK-MTR route title\n| engname = Tung Chung line\n| chiname = \u6771\u6d8c\u7dab\n| line    = Tung Chung\n}}\n| image       = A Train Tung Chung Line 15-07-2017.jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| image_alt   =\n| caption     = Tung Chung line train approaching [[Sunny Bay station]]\n| type        = [[Commuter Rail]]\n| system      = [[MTR]]\n| locale      = [[Districts of Hong Kong|Districts]]: [[Central and Western District|Central and Western]], [[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]], [[Sham Shui Po District|Sham Shui Po]], [[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]], [[Tsuen Wan District|Tsuen Wan]], [[Islands District, Hong Kong|Islands]]\n| start       = [[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]\n| end         = [[Tung Chung station|Tung Chung]]\n| stations    = 8\n| open        = {{start date|1998|06|21|df=y}}\n| speed_km/h  = 135\n\n| close       =\n| depot       = [[Siu Ho Wan]]\n| stock       = {{plainlist|\n* [[MTR Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU|Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU]]\n* [[MTR Rotem EMU|Rotem EMU]]\n}}\n| linelength  = {{convert|31.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|1432mm|lk=on}}\n| electrification          = 1.5 [[Volt|kV]] [[Direct current|DC]]\n| map         = [[File:Tung Chung Line.svg|x60px|center]]<hr />{{Tung Chung line RDT}}\n| map_state   = expanded\n| ridership2  = 236,900 daily average <br>(weekdays, September 2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekday patronage of MTR heavy rail network from September 1 to 27 and September 28 to October 25, 2014|url=http://gia.info.gov.hk/general/201410/29/P201410290671_0671_136426.pdf|publisher=[[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]]|accessdate=15 April 2015|date=29 October 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab|l=East (of a) branch of a river \u2014 \u6771\u6d8c|p=D\u014dngch\u014dng xi\u00e0n|j=dung1 cung1 sin3|y=d\u016bng ch\u016bng sin}}\n\nThe '''Tung Chung line''' is one of the eleven rapid transit lines of the [[MTR]] system in [[Hong Kong]], linking [[Tung Chung]] with [[Hong Kong Island]]. A part of the Tung Chung line was built along with the [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]] and the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]]. The line currently travels through eight stations in 27 minutes along its route. The line is indicated by the colour orange.\n\n== History ==\nIn October 1989, the [[Hong Kong]] government announced [[Airport Core Programme|plans]] to build a new [[Hong Kong International Airport|airport]] on the remote island of [[Chek Lap Kok]] to replace the overcrowded [[Kai Tak International Airport]] at the heart of [[Kowloon]]. \n\nAs part of the initiative, the government invited the MTR Corporation to build a rail link to the new airport dubbed the Lantau Airport Railway. The project initially saw opposition from the Chinese government as it feared the construction would drain the monetary reserve of the Hong Kong government and leave the Chinese with nothing after the British handed the territory over in 1997. \n\nBoth the Chinese and British governments reached an agreement and construction commenced in November 1994.\n\nThe Lantau Airport rail link consists of two train lines, the Tung Chung line and the [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]]. Both lines deploy the same [[MTR A-Stock EMU|rolling stock]] with minor differences in interior fittings and liveries.\n\nOn 21 June 1998, the Tung Chung line was officially opened by [[Hong Kong Chief Executive|Chief Executive]] [[Tung Chee-hwa]], and service commenced the next day.\n\nOn 16 December 2003, an open house for charity took place at the recently completed [[Nam Cheong station]], an interchange between the Tung Chung line and soon to be opened [[West Rail line|West Rail&nbsp;line]]. The station then closed on 19 December 2003 in preparation for the opening of the new West Rail Line, and it was officially opened to public on 20 December 2003. Since then, the number of cars per train has increased from seven to eight to accommodate the additional patronage.\n\n[[Sunny Bay station]] opened on 1 June 2005 as an interchange for the [[Disneyland Resort line|Disneyland Resort&nbsp;line]]. The resort opened its door two months after the station became operational.\n\nBetween 2006 and 2007, four new [[MTR Rotem EMU|trains]] entered service to improve service frequency. The first train was delivered on 9 February 2006 and entered service on 12 June 2006. Modifications were added to the platforms to accommodate the new trains, which are a few millimetres wider than the original rolling stock.\n\n== Route map ==\n{|border=0 style=\"margin:auto\"\n|[[File:LAR ga map.png|center|thumb|upright=3|MTR Tung Chung line and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] route map]]\n|}\n\n== Route description ==\nUnlike most other railway lines in the system, the Tung Chung Line travels mostly above ground and spans a greater distance. The line shares most of its trackage with the [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] and diverges in Tung Chung. \n\nThe line travels underground from [[Hong Kong station]] to [[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon station]] across the harbour; then surfaces to the ground to reach [[Olympic station]]. Trains continue to travel above ground along the [[West Kowloon Expressway]] and stops at [[Nam Cheong station]], then stops at [[Lai King station]] on a viaduct. Thereafter the line crosses the [[Rambler Channel]] and stops at [[Tsing Yi station]] on Tsing Yi Island. \n\nTrains then enter a tunnel through the hills of the island and continues of on the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]] and the [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]] into Lantau Island.\n\nOnce on the island, the line travels adjacent to the [[North Lantau Highway|North Lantau Expressway]]. The Airport Express splits from Tung Chung Line at the outskirts of Tung Chung and travel on its dedicates tracks.\n\nThe gap between Sunny Bay and Tung Chug is roughly 10km and the journey takes approximately 6 minutes to complete.\n\nSome outbound trains do not continue to Lantau but terminate at Tsing Yi station due to the capacity constraint of the Tsing Ma Bridge, in which it only allows one train to pass at all times. <ref>{{cite document|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr09-10/english/panels/tp/tp_rdp/papers/tp_rdp1117cb1-417-1-e.pdf|title=Legislative Council Panel on Transport, Subcommittee on Matters Relating to Railways, Airport Railway Capacity|publisher=Legislative Council of Hong Kong|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:MTR-TungChung-Train.JPG|Tung Chung line Train at [[Sunny Bay station]]\nFile:Tung Chung Line Train.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR A-Stock EMU|A-Stock Train]]\nFile:HK Tung Chung Line Train.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR K-Stock EMU|K-Stock Train]]\nFile:K Train Tung Chung Line 15-07-2017.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR K-Stock EMU|K-Stock Train]]\nFile:MTR TUC (13).JPG|Exterior of [[Tung Chung station]]\nFile:Lai King Station 2015 part1.jpg|Upper platform level of [[Lai King station]]\n</gallery>\n<gallery>\nFile:Nam Cheong Station 2008.jpg|[[Nam Cheong station]]; interchange with [[West Rail line]]\nFile:HK MTR Olympic Station Concourse.jpg|[[Olympic station]] concourse\nFile:HKMTR KOW Elevator 20070922.jpg|[[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon station]], Tung Chung line platform\nFile:HongKongStationplatform1 20070922.jpg|[[Hong Kong station]], Tung Chung line platform\n</gallery>\n\n== Stations ==\nThe following is a list of the stations on the Tung Chung line.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 75%; margin: 0.5em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=2| [[Livery]] and name\n! [[Districts of Hong Kong|District]]\n! Connections\n! Opening date\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-top:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Tung Chung}}; border-bottom:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Tung Chung}};\"| Tung Chung line\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF;\"|\n|'''[[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]'''\n|[[Central and Western District|Central and Western]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}<small><br/>[[Central station (MTR)|Central station]] for {{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}} and {{rcb|MTR|Island|yes}}</small>\n|rowspan=3|22 June 1998\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#EEEDED;\"|\n|'''[[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon]]'''\n|rowspan=2|[[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#4682B4;\"|\n|'''[[Olympic station|Olympic]]'''\n|\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF80;\"|\n|'''[[Nam Cheong station|Nam Cheong]]'''\n|[[Sham Shui Po District|Sham Shui Po]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|West Rail|yes}}\n|20 December 2003\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#BB2200;\"|\n|'''[[Lai King station|Lai King]]'''\n|rowspan=2|[[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}}\n|10 May 1982 <small>(Tsuen Wan line)</small><br/>22 June 1998 <small>(Tung Chung line)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#89B0B7;\"|\n|'''[[Tsing Yi station|Tsing Yi]]'''\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}\n|22 June 1998\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#808080;\"|\n|'''[[Sunny Bay station|Sunny Bay]]'''\n|[[Tsuen Wan]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Disneyland Resort|yes}}\n|1 June 2005\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#8040C0;\"|\n|'''[[Tung Chung station|Tung Chung]]'''\n|[[Islands District|Islands]]\n|[[Ngong Ping Cable Car]]\n|22 June 1998\n|}\n\n==Design limitations==\nWhen the then [[British Hong Kong|colonial government]] announced its plans to build the airport rail link, the Chinese government raised concerns of the significant capital outgoings. In 1994, a few years before the [[Hong Kong Handover|handover]], both British and Chinese governments reached an agreement on the conditions of the following cost saving measures: <ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}{{cite news|author=MTR Service Update|title=\u70ba\u751a\u9ebc\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab\u7e3d\u662f\u73ed\u6b21\u758f\u843d\uff1f|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/11/26/24965|accessdate=2012-11-28|date=2012-11-26}}</ref>\n\n* The airport rail link was originally designed to accommodate four tracks, two each for the Airport Express and Tung Chung Line. It was later reduced to two tracks where both services share the same trackage. As a result, signal failures can affect both services.\n\n* Reduction on train traffic capacity on [[Tsing Ma Bridge]], [[Ma Wan Viaduct]], and [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]]) means only one train can travel on either direction on any given time. The minimum [[headway]] between trains comes to 2 minutes 15 seconds, and forces some Tung Chung Line services from crossing the bridges into Lantau and terminate at Tsing Yi.\n\n* The signalling system is not capable of giving priority to the limited-stop Airport Express trains. Tung Chung Line trains  would sometimes stop at [[Sunny Bay Station]] for an extended period of time to give way to the Airport Express trains.\n\n* The power supply system restricts the number of trains running between Kowloon and Lai King stations. The system can accommodate a maximum of one Airport Express train and two Tung Chung trains to travel on both directions at the same time. This increases the minimum headway on the Tung Chung Line is 3.5 minutes.\n\n==Future development==\n{{main|North Island line|Tung Chung West station}}\n\nThe Tung Chung line was designed to facilitate an extension from [[Hong Kong station]] eastward. According to the Rail Projects Under Planning 2000 released by Hong Kong Highways Department, three new stations, [[Tamar station|Tamar]], [[Exhibition Centre station (MTR)|Exhibition Centre]] and [[Causeway Bay North station|Causeway Bay North]], will form part of the extension. The line will then connect [[North Point station]] and merge into the [[Tseung Kwan O line]]. However 14 years later on the Railway Development Strategy 2014 Tamar station would become the terminus for both the Tseung Kwan O line and Tung Chung line while Exhibition and Causeway Bay North stations would be served by the Tseung Kwan O line.\n\nResidents of [[Yat Tung Estate]] have appealed to the government to extend the Tung Chung line to [[Tung Chung West station]] near Yat Tung to ease their transportation problems. Yat Tung currently has 40,000 residents. They claimed that when they moved in 11 years ago, the Housing Bureau's documents indicated a MTR station at the estate. The residents currently have to take a 10-minute bus journey to [[Tung Chung station]].<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}[http://paper.wenweipo.com/2011/05/25/HK1105250005.htm \u9038\u6771\u90a8\u5c45\u6c11\u8981\u6c42\u5efa\u6e2f\u9435\u7ad9] ''Wen Wei Po''. 25 May 2011.</ref>\n\nOn April 7th 2020, it was announced by the Hong Kong government that the Tung Chung line will be extended by 1.3 kilometres to [[Tung Chung West station]], as well as building an intermediate station in [[Tung Chung East station]]. The government has put the estimated cost for the rail extension in Tung Chung at HK$19 billion. Detailed design and planning is underway and is expected to take three years, with construction of the project is expected to commence in 2023, and take six years to complete.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1519400-20200407.htm?spTabChangeable=0|title=Tung Chung Line extension to cost HK$19bn: govt - RTHK|website=news.rthk.hk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Tung Chung line}}\n* [[List of areas of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Transport in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{MTR}}\n{{Tung Chung line navbox}}\n{{North Island line navbox}}\n{{Eastern Guangdong & Hong Kong transit}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n| structure       = Tunnel crossings\n| place           = [[Victoria Harbour]]\n| bridge          = Tung Chung line and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] between [[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon]] and [[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]\n| upstream        = [[Western Harbour Crossing]]\n| upstream text   = West\n| downstream      = [[Tsuen Wan line]] between [[Tsim Sha Tsui station|Tsim Sha Tsui]