lative Council of Hong Kong]]|accessdate=15 April 2015|date=29 October 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab|l=East (of a) branch of a river \u2014 \u6771\u6d8c|p=D\u014dngch\u014dng xi\u00e0n|j=dung1 cung1 sin3|y=d\u016bng ch\u016bng sin}}\n\nThe '''Tung Chung line''' is one of the eleven rapid transit lines of the [[MTR]] system in [[Hong Kong]], linking [[Tung Chung]] with [[Hong Kong Island]]. A part of the Tung Chung line was built along with the [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]] and the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]]. The line currently travels through eight stations in 27 minutes along its route. The line is indicated by the colour orange.\n\n== History ==\nIn October 1989, the [[Hong Kong]] government announced [[Airport Core Programme|plans]] to build a new [[Hong Kong International Airport|airport]] on the remote island of [[Chek Lap Kok]] to replace the overcrowded [[Kai Tak International Airport]] at the heart of [[Kowloon]]. \n\nAs part of the initiative, the government invited the MTR Corporation to build a rail link to the new airport dubbed the Lantau Airport Railway. The project initially saw opposition from the Chinese government as it feared the construction would drain the monetary reserve of the Hong Kong government and leave the Chinese with nothing after the British handed the territory over in 1997. \n\nBoth the Chinese and British governments reached an agreement and construction commenced in November 1994.\n\nThe Lantau Airport rail link consists of two train lines, the Tung Chung line and the [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]]. Both lines deploy the same [[MTR A-Stock EMU|rolling stock]] with minor differences in interior fittings and liveries.\n\nOn 21 June 1998, the Tung Chung line was officially opened by [[Hong Kong Chief Executive|Chief Executive]] [[Tung Chee-hwa]], and service commenced the next day.\n\nOn 16 December 2003, an open house for charity took place at the recently completed [[Nam Cheong station]], an interchange between the Tung Chung line and soon to be opened [[West Rail line|West Rail&nbsp;line]]. The station then closed on 19 December 2003 in preparation for the opening of the new West Rail Line, and it was officially opened to public on 20 December 2003. Since then, the number of cars per train has increased from seven to eight to accommodate the additional patronage.\n\n[[Sunny Bay station]] opened on 1 June 2005 as an interchange for the [[Disneyland Resort line|Disneyland Resort&nbsp;line]]. The resort opened its door two months after the station became operational.\n\nBetween 2006 and 2007, four new [[MTR Rotem EMU|trains]] entered service to improve service frequency. The first train was delivered on 9 February 2006 and entered service on 12 June 2006. Modifications were added to the platforms to accommodate the new trains, which are a few millimetres wider than the original rolling stock.\n\n== Route map ==\n{|border=0 style=\"margin:auto\"\n|[[File:LAR ga map.png|center|thumb|upright=3|MTR Tung Chung line and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] route map]]\n|}\n\n== Route description ==\nUnlike most other railway lines in the system, the Tung Chung Line travels mostly above ground and spans a greater distance. The line shares most of its trackage with the [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] and diverges in Tung Chung. \n\nThe line travels underground from [[Hong Kong station]] to [[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon station]] across the harbour; then surfaces to the ground to reach [[Olympic station]]. Trains continue to travel above ground along the [[West Kowloon Expressway]] and stops at [[Nam Cheong station]], then stops at [[Lai King station]] on a viaduct. Thereafter the line crosses the [[Rambler Channel]] and stops at [[Tsing Yi station]] on Tsing Yi Island. \n\nTrains then enter a tunnel through the hills of the island and continues of on the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]] and the [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]] into Lantau Island.\n\nOnce on the island, the line travels adjacent to the [[North Lantau Highway|North Lantau Expressway]]. The Airport Express splits from Tung Chung Line at the outskirts of Tung Chung and travel on its dedicates tracks.\n\nThe gap between Sunny Bay and Tung Chug is roughly 10km and the journey takes approximately 6 minutes to complete.\n\nSome outbound trains do not continue to Lantau but terminate at Tsing Yi station due to the capacity constraint of the Tsing Ma Bridge, in which it only allows one train to pass at all times. <ref>{{cite document|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr09-10/english/panels/tp/tp_rdp/papers/tp_rdp1117cb1-417-1-e.pdf|title=Legislative Council Panel on Transport, Subcommittee on Matters Relating to Railways, Airport Railway Capacity|publisher=Legislative Council of Hong Kong|date=17 November 2009|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:MTR-TungChung-Train.JPG|Tung Chung line Train at [[Sunny Bay station]]\nFile:Tung Chung Line Train.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR A-Stock EMU|A-Stock Train]]\nFile:HK Tung Chung Line Train.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR K-Stock EMU|K-Stock Train]]\nFile:K Train Tung Chung Line 15-07-2017.jpg|Tung Chung line [[MTR K-Stock EMU|K-Stock Train]]\nFile:MTR TUC (13).JPG|Exterior of [[Tung Chung station]]\nFile:Lai King Station 2015 part1.jpg|Upper platform level of [[Lai King station]]\n</gallery>\n<gallery>\nFile:Nam Cheong Station 2008.jpg|[[Nam Cheong station]]; interchange with [[West Rail line]]\nFile:HK MTR Olympic Station Concourse.jpg|[[Olympic station]] concourse\nFile:HKMTR KOW Elevator 20070922.jpg|[[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon station]], Tung Chung line platform\nFile:HongKongStationplatform1 20070922.jpg|[[Hong Kong station]], Tung Chung line platform\n</gallery>\n\n== Stations ==\nThe following is a list of the stations on the Tung Chung line.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 75%; margin: 0.5em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=2| [[Livery]] and name\n! [[Districts of Hong Kong|District]]\n! Connections\n! Opening date\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-top:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Tung Chung}}; border-bottom:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Tung Chung}};\"| Tung Chung line\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF;\"|\n|'''[[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]'''\n|[[Central and Western District|Central and Western]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}<small><br/>[[Central station (MTR)|Central station]] for {{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}} and {{rcb|MTR|Island|yes}}</small>\n|rowspan=3|22 June 1998\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#EEEDED;\"|\n|'''[[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon]]'''\n|rowspan=2|[[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#4682B4;\"|\n|'''[[Olympic station|Olympic]]'''\n|\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FFFF80;\"|\n|'''[[Nam Cheong station|Nam Cheong]]'''\n|[[Sham Shui Po District|Sham Shui Po]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|West Rail|yes}}\n|20 December 2003\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#BB2200;\"|\n|'''[[Lai King station|Lai King]]'''\n|rowspan=2|[[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}}\n|10 May 1982 <small>(Tsuen Wan line)</small><br/>22 June 1998 <small>(Tung Chung line)</small>\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#89B0B7;\"|\n|'''[[Tsing Yi station|Tsing Yi]]'''\n|{{rcb|MTR|Airport Express|yes}}\n|22 June 1998\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#808080;\"|\n|'''[[Sunny Bay station|Sunny Bay]]'''\n|[[Tsuen Wan]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Disneyland Resort|yes}}\n|1 June 2005\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#8040C0;\"|\n|'''[[Tung Chung station|Tung Chung]]'''\n|[[Islands District|Islands]]\n|[[Ngong Ping Cable Car]]\n|22 June 1998\n|}\n\n==Design limitations==\nWhen the then [[British Hong Kong|colonial government]] announced its plans to build the airport rail link, the Chinese government raised concerns of the significant capital outgoings. In 1994, a few years before the [[Hong Kong Handover|handover]], both British and Chinese governments reached an agreement on the conditions of the following cost saving measures: <ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}{{cite news|author=MTR Service Update|title=\u70ba\u751a\u9ebc\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab\u7e3d\u662f\u73ed\u6b21\u758f\u843d\uff1f|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/11/26/24965|accessdate=2012-11-28|date=2012-11-26}}</ref>\n\n* The airport rail link was originally designed to accommodate four tracks, two each for the Airport Express and Tung Chung Line. It was later reduced to two tracks where both services share the same trackage. As a result, signal failures can affect both services.\n\n* Reduction on train traffic capacity on [[Tsing Ma Bridge]], [[Ma Wan Viaduct]], and [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]]) means only one train can travel on either direction on any given time. The minimum [[headway]] between trains comes to 2 minutes 15 seconds, and forces some Tung Chung Line services from crossing the bridges into Lantau and terminate at Tsung Yi. \n\n* The signalling system is not capable of giving priority to the limited-stop Airport Express trains. Tung Chung Line trains  would sometimes stop at [[Sunny Bay Station]] for an extended period of time to give way to the Airport Express trains.\n\n* The power supply system restricts the number of trains running between Kowloon and Lai King stations. The system can accommodate a maximum of one Airport Express train and two Tung Chung trains to travel on both directions at the same time. This increases the minimum headway on the Tung Chung Line is 3.5 minutes.\n\n==Future development==\n{{main|North Island line|Tung Chung West station}}\n\nThe Tung Chung line was designed to facilitate an extension from [[Hong Kong station]] eastward. According to the Rail Projects Under Planning 2000 released by Hong Kong Highways Department, three new stations, [[Tamar station|Tamar]], [[Exhibition Centre station (MTR)|Exhibition Centre]] and [[Causeway Bay North station|Causeway Bay North]], will form part of the extension. The line will then connect [[North Point station]] and merge into the [[Tseung Kwan O line]]. However 14 years later on the Railway Development Strategy 2014 Tamar station would become the terminus for both the Tseung Kwan O line and Tung Chung line while Exhibition and Causeway Bay North stations would be served by the Tseung Kwan O line.\n\nResidents of [[Yat Tung Estate]] have appealed to the government to extend the Tung Chung line to [[Tung Chung West station]] near Yat Tung to ease their transportation problems. Yat Tung currently has 40,000 residents. They claimed that when they moved in 11 years ago, the Housing Bureau's documents indicated a MTR station at the estate. The residents currently have to take a 10-minute bus journey to [[Tung Chung station]].<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}[http://paper.wenweipo.com/2011/05/25/HK1105250005.htm \u9038\u6771\u90a8\u5c45\u6c11\u8981\u6c42\u5efa\u6e2f\u9435\u7ad9] ''Wen Wei Po''. 25 May 2011.</ref>\n\nOn April 7th 2020, it was announced by the Hong Kong government that the Tung Chung line will be extended by 1.3 kilometres to [[Tung Chung West station]], as well as building an intermediate station in [[Tung Chung East station]]. The government has put the estimated cost for the rail extension in Tung Chung at HK$19 billion. Detailed design and planning is underway and is expected to take three years, with construction of the project is expected to commence in 2023, and take six years to complete. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1519400-20200407.htm?spTabChangeable=0|title=Tung Chung Line extension to cost HK$19bn: govt - RTHK|website=news.rthk.hk|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Tung Chung line}}\n* [[List of areas of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Transport in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{MTR}}\n{{Tung Chung line navbox}}\n{{North Island line navbox}}\n{{Eastern Guangdong & Hong Kong transit}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n| structure       = Tunnel crossings\n| place           = [[Victoria Harbour]]\n| bridge          = Tung Chung line and [[Airport Express (MTR)|Airport Express]] between [[Kowloon station (MTR)|Kowloon]] and [[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]\n| upstream        = [[Western Harbour Crossing]]\n| upstream text   = West\n| downstream      = [[Tsuen Wan line]] between [[Tsim Sha Tsui station|Tsim Sha Tsui]] and [[Admiralty station (MTR)|Admiralty]]\n| downstream text = East\n}}\n\n[[Category:MTR lines]]\n[[Category:Tung Chung line|*]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1998]]\n[[Category:Regional rail in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1432 mm gauge railways in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Hongkonguser1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tung_Chung_line"}
{"title_page": "21 West Street", "text_new": "{{Short description|Residential skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = 21 West Street\n | image = Oldnycmay01b.jpg\n | caption = 21 West Street, with [[Downtown Athletic Club]]<br />at right (partly obscured), May 2001\n | location = 21 [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]], New York City\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|42|23|N|74|00|56|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =Lower Manhattan#New York City\n| map_label =21 West Street\n  | area = less than one acre\n | built = 1929\u20131931\n  | architect = [[Starrett & van Vleck]]\n  | architecture = [[Art Deco]]\n  | added = March 12, 1999\n  | refnum = 99000316<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n | designated_other2_date = June 16, 1998\n | designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n | designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n | designated_other2_number = 1999\n | designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n  }}\n'''21 West Street''', also known as '''Le Rivage Apartments''', is a 33-story building located in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]], on Morris Street between [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] and [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]]. It was built in 1929\u20131931 as a [[Speculative development|speculative]] office tower development in anticipation of an increased demand for office space in Lower Manhattan. The building was converted into apartments in 1997 and was renamed Le Rivage.\n\nThe building has an [[Art Deco]] design with many lavish architectural finishes and a series of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] which taper toward the top floors. It was designed by [[Starrett & van Vleck]], who at the same time designed the adjacent [[Downtown Athletic Club]]. 21 West Street was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1999 and designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998.\n\n== Site ==\n21 West Street is located near the southernmost point of [[Manhattan Island]], closest to its western shore. The building faces [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, Morris Street to the north, and [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]] and the [[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]] portal to the east. It is adjacent to the [[Downtown Athletic Club]] building at 18\u201320 West Street to the south,{{efn|Address numbers on the east side of West Street run consecutively because the west side of the street was formerly on the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1984.pdf|title=West Street Building|date=1998-05-19|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05|page=7}}</ref> Therefore, 18\u201320 West Street is adjacent to 21 West Street. In the area's standard [[House numbering#North America|address numbering]] system, odd- and even-numbered addresses are on opposite sides of the street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\"/>}} which also occupies the entire block between West and Washington Streets.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/|title=NYCityMap|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of New York City|NYC.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/04/17/archives/latest-skyscraper-for-lower-manhattan-thirtyonestory-structure-will.html|title=Latest Skyscraper For Lower Manhattan; Thirty-one-Story Structure Will Occupy Block With Whitehall Building and Athletic Club.|date=April 17, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[Land lot|lot]] has a frontage of {{Convert|75|ft||abbr=}} on each of West and Washington Streets, and {{Convert|179|ft||abbr=}} on Morris Street, covering a total area of {{Convert|13500|ft2||abbr=}}.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe building stands on filled land along the shore of the [[North River (Hudson River)|North River]] (an archaic name for the southernmost portion of the [[Hudson River]]). The surrounding neighborhood, the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], was the first part of Manhattan to be developed as part of [[New Netherland]] and later New York City; its population growth led city officials to add land on Manhattan's shore by filling and [[land reclamation]] in the 18th and 19th centuries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> As the North River shoreline was deeper and had a denser concentration of buildings than the East River shoreline on the east side of Manhattan Island,<ref name=\"NYCL (DAC) p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> the land under 21 West Street was not filled until 1835, when debris from the [[Great Fire of New York]] was dumped there.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> As a result of the land filling, 21 West Street was constructed without a basement,<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-No_Basement-1930\"/> which was \"a decidedly rare feature\" in New York City buildings, hence the need to import steam and electricity.<ref name=\"NYT-No_Basement-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/12/07/archives/west-st-building-has-no-basement-steam-and-electricity-from-outside.html|title=West St. Building Has No Basement; Steam and Electricity From Outside Sources for Thirty-one Story Structure|date=December 7, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 13, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The site of 21 West Street was first occupied by small landowners who built houses in the area.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The surrounding neighborhood became a financial and shipping hub during the late 19th century;<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> as the Financial District became more densely developed, the residential landowners moved uptown and their former lands were combined to build larger commercial buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 75 - 21 West Street.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Facade detail showing corner windows at right]]\n\n21 West Street is 31 stories tall.{{efn|The [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] refers to the floor above ground level as the \"second story\", with the double-height ground floor considered as one story, and thus regards 21 West Street as being 31 stories tall.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The [[National Park Service]] refers to the floor above ground level as the \"third story\", considering the ground floor as the equivalent of two stories, and thus regards 21 West Street as being a 32-story building.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />}} It was designed in the [[Art Deco]] style<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> by [[Starrett & van Vleck]], who at the same time designed the adjacent Downtown Athletic Club building. Starrett & van Vleck had already designed several New York City department stores, including the [[Lord & Taylor building]], the [[Bloomingdale's|Bloomingdale's building]], and the [[Saks Fifth Avenue|Saks Fifth Avenue building]].<ref name=\"NYCL (DAC) p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=3}}</ref>\n\n=== Form ===\nThe building has a ground-story [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] which overhangs much of the Morris Street sidewalk, giving the impression that pedestrians have been transported inside the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> There are numerous [[storefront]]s beneath the arcade, as well as the entrance to the building's [[Lobby (room)|lobby]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\nAs mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]], the design of 21 West Street features six [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> creating the impression that the building tapers off as it ascends.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The setbacks are located on Washington Street above the 10th and 16th floors, at the northwest and northeast corners above the 21st floor, and on all sides above the 26th, 29th, and 30th floors.<ref name=\"floor-count\" group=\"lower-alpha\">In this article, the floor above ground level is referred to as the \"second floor\", even though the ground level is the equivalent of two stories. All subsequent stories are referred to using this same pattern.</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|National Park Service|1999|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL pp. 5-6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|pp=5\u20136}}</ref>\n\n=== Facade ===\nThe [[facade]] of 21 West Street was designed with molded and oversized brick \"to emphasize the structural lines and to enrich the texture of the materials\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Brick and [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] were used in red, orange, and yellow tones,<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> a design feature influenced by [[Harvey Wiley Corbett|Harvey Wiley Corbett's]] plan for the [[Master Apartments]] in the Upper West Side of Manhattan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> For instance, the light-tan vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] highlight the building's vertical dimension, while other brick patterns give the impression of a \"skin\", including the horizontal lines of the [[spandrel]]s between the floors.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> At each setback and on the three lower levels, the [[parapet]]s have various designs of molded brick to provide [[Surface finish|surface texture]] to the building's exterior.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The southern facade is hidden behind the Downtown Athletic Club building to the south.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref>\n\nThe corners of the building were outfitted with windows wrapping around the edge at a 90-degree angle, instead of structural columns as had been provided in previous buildings, making 21 West Street possibly the first commercial building in the U.S. to have wrap-around corner windows.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Bruner1930\">{{cite journal|last=Bruner|first=Warren D.|date=June 1930|title=Office Layouts for Tenants|url=https://www.usmodernist.org/AF/AF-1930-06-2.pdf|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=52|pages=905 (PDF 67)}}</ref>{{efn|The Landmarks Preservation Commission described this as a fine distinction: the [[Master Apartments]] on the [[Upper West Side]] (built 1928\u20131929) was cited as the first ''residential'' skyscraper with corner windows,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\"/> and the Child's Restaurant building at [[604 Fifth Avenue]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]] (built 1925) was cited as the first building of any kind with such windows.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/25/realestate/25scape.html|title=The History of 3 Midtown Neighbors|last=Gray|first=Christopher|date=July 25, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 3, 2020|page=RE9||language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}} Prior to the construction of 21 West Street, corner windows had only been used on residential structures.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\n[[File:Building at 21 West Street 2013-10-14 13-21-21.jpg|thumb|Underside of one of the corners, facing the arcade on Morris Street]]\n\nDespite its address, 21 West Street's primary entrance is at the center of the Morris Street facade, beneath the one-story arcade, which includes ten [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] at ground level. Multicolored mosaics are located on the ceiling of the arcade.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> The arcade, storefronts, and main entrance contain decorative metalworks painted in silver and gold tones, which extend into the interior, described by the [[National Park Service]] as \"an unusual design feature\".<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> The piers and interior walls of the arcade are outfitted with bronze panels and lighting installations. The arcade's arches mostly consist of stepped brick, except for the fifth bay from Washington Street, which is a square marble-framed arch that leads to the main entrance. The spandrels above the arcade are textured in a chevron (V-shaped) design with tan and purple brick. The arcade continues in reduced form on the West and Washington Street facades, each being five bays wide.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />\n\nThe second floor<ref name=\"floor-count\" group=\"lower-alpha\" /> has three windows per bay, with wrap-around windows at the corners; the second-floor bays are separated by purple and tan brick piers.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> Above the ground floor, each floor of 21 West Street generally contains two rolled steel windows per bay, with wrap-around windows at the corners, each of these windows having four panes, two on each side.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> Below the setbacks on the 21st and 26th floors, the corners facing Morris Street are replaced with a single diagonal [[chamfer]]ed bay.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" />\n\n=== Features ===\nHaving constructed 21 West Street as a [[speculative development]] in anticipation of growing demand for office space in lower Manhattan,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=9}}</ref> the building's developers aimed to attract potential tenants through the unique design of the structure.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> When built, 21 West Street included high-speed elevators and other innovations \"to contribute to the comfort and convenience of its tenants\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 1931|title=21 West Street Office Building, New York City|url=|journal=Architecture and Building|volume=63|pages=90\u201391}}</ref> A lobby, {{Frac|1|1|2}} stories high, is located on the north side of the ground floor, linking to the two elevator banks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> The lobby has a colorful marble mosaic on its floor, depicting the old street grid of lower Manhattan in a style similar to a [[Nautical chart|mariner's map]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> There are bronze lighting installations near the elevator banks, decorated with waves and shell motifs.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\nSince its conversion to an apartment building, the interior of 21 West Street has included a [[Terrace (building)|terrace]] on the 34th floor, a play area for children, and a fitness room.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/le-rivage/|title=Le Rivage - TRD Research|date=March 13, 2019|website=The Real Deal|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The rooms were created from former office spaces; for instance, the play area was previously a [[Changing room|locker room]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Joanne|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/24/realestate/older-buildings-add-amenities-to-compete.html|title=Insert a Gym, Then a Lounge: Older Buildings Add Amenities|date=April 22, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe construction of 21 West Street occurred when the Financial District was being expanded as a commercial area. The construction of the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]]'s [[Elevated railway|elevated railroad lines]], and later the [[New York City Subway]], had spurred the relocation of the area's residential population uptown in the late 19th and early 20th centuries; the [[tenement]]s that developed at the edges of the Financial District were being demolished and replaced with office buildings.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" />\n\nThe building was owned by the 21 West Street Corporation, which had close ties with the maritime industry along the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> It was developed by civil engineer Alfred Rheinstein.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/28/archives/alfred-rheinstein-dead-at-85-founded-construction-concern-exhead-of.html|title=Alfred Rheinstein Dead at 85; Founded Construction Concern|date=May 28, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Work began on the structure in 1929,<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> the foundations had been laid by April 1930,<ref name=\":0\" /> and building work was completed in 1931.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Real estate agents William A. White & Sons were hired to rent out the space in 21 West Street.<ref name=\":0\" /> After the building's completion, the owners identified tenants in the maritime and shipping industries, including lawyers, transport companies, and import/export companies associated with the sector. In addition, naval architecture firm [[Gibbs & Cox]] was headquartered at the building for over 30 years.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Other early tenants included the Peruvian [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] in New York City,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1940/03/26/archives/peruvian-offices-to-move-uptown-consulate-for-11-years-in-21-west.html|title=Peruvian Offices To Move Uptown; Consulate, for 11 Years in 21 West St., Leases Quarters in 10 Rockefeller Plaza|date=March 26, 1940|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the Moran Towing and Transportation Company,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/12/30/archives/shipping-offices-taken-downtown-rector-and-west-street-office.html|title=Shipping Offices Taken Downtown; Rector and West Street Office Quarters Are Leased by New Tenants|date=December 30, 1943|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the Shepard Steamship Company,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/02/10/archives/shepard-offices-moved-steamship-company-gets-new-quarters-at-21.html|title=Shepard Offices Moved; Steamship Company Gets New Quarters at 21 West Street|date=February 10, 1947|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the Hedger Transportation Corporation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/10/22/archives/financial-firms-moving-three-lease-in-21-west-street-and-goldman.html|title=Financial Firms Moving; Three Lease in 21 West Street and Goldman Sachs Building|date=October 22, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Around 1950, the main entrance was modified and a [[heating, ventilation, and air conditioning]] system was installed.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the residential development and management firm, Rose Associates, announced plans to convert 21 West Street into a 293-unit apartment building called Le Rivage. It was to be the firm's first project in 10 years and its first Manhattan project below [[8th Street and St. Mark's Place|8th Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Garbarine|first=Rachelle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/11/nyregion/rose-associates-enters-the-conversion-market.html|title=Rose Associates Enters The Conversion Market|date=July 11, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> and was listed on the National Park Service's [[National Register of Historic Places]] the following year,<ref name=\"NPS p. 1\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> at which time it was recorded in the register that 21 West Street had been \"abandoned for over a decade\".<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> When the building was damaged in [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, residents' rents were temporarily lowered.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\" /> The residential units in 21 West Street were partially renovated in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/10/realestate/the-financial-district-gains-momentum.html|title=The Financial District Gains Momentum|date=August 8, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal box|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[Art Deco architecture of New York City]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1999.pdf|title=21 West Street Building|date=June 16, 1998|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2075.pdf|title=Downtown Athletic Club Building|date=November 14, 2000|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/99000316.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Building at 21 West Street|date=February 11, 1999|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|1999}}}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|21 West Street}}\n* {{official|http://www.21west.com}}\n* [http://www.rosenyc.com/rentals/21-west-street/ Rose Associates, Inc. - Building Management Company Site]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n{{New York City Historic Sites}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:West Side Highway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Residential skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = 21 West Street\n | image = Oldnycmay01b.jpg\n | caption = 21 West Street, with [[Downtown Athletic Club]]<br />at right (partly obscured), May 2001\n | location = 21 [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]], New York City\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|42|23|N|74|00|56|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin =Lower Manhattan#New York City\n| map_label =21 West Street\n  | area = less than one acre\n | built = 1929\u20131931\n  | architect = [[Starrett & van Vleck]]\n  | architecture = [[Art Deco]]\n  | added = March 12, 1999\n  | refnum = 99000316<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_name = NYC Landmark\n | designated_other2_date = June 16, 1998\n | designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n | designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n | designated_other2_number = 1999\n | designated_other2_color = #ffe978\n  }}\n'''21 West Street''', also known as '''Le Rivage Apartments''', is a 33-story building located in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]], on Morris Street between [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] and [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]]. It was built in 1929\u20131931 as a [[Speculative development|speculative]] office tower development in anticipation of an increased demand for office space in Lower Manhattan. The building was converted into apartments in 1997 and was renamed Le Rivage.\n\nThe building has an [[Art Deco]] design with many lavish architectural finishes and a series of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] which taper toward the top floors. It was designed by [[Starrett & van Vleck]], who at the same time designed the adjacent [[Downtown Athletic Club]]. 21 West Street was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1999 and designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998.\n\n== Site ==\n21 West Street is located near the southernmost point of [[Manhattan Island]], closest to its western shore. The building faces [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] to the west, Morris Street to the north, and [[Washington Street (Manhattan)|Washington Street]] and the [[Brooklyn\u2013Battery Tunnel]] portal to the east. It is adjacent to the [[Downtown Athletic Club]] building at 18\u201320 West Street to the south,{{efn|Address numbers on the east side of West Street run consecutively because the west side of the street was formerly on the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1984.pdf|title=West Street Building|date=1998-05-19|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05|page=7}}</ref> Therefore, 18\u201320 West Street is adjacent to 21 West Street. In the area's standard [[House numbering#North America|address numbering]] system, odd- and even-numbered addresses are on opposite sides of the street.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\"/>}} which also occupies the entire block between West and Washington Streets.<ref name=\"NYC.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nyc.gov/doitt/nycitymap/|title=NYCityMap|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Government of New York City|NYC.gov]]|publisher=[[New York City Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/04/17/archives/latest-skyscraper-for-lower-manhattan-thirtyonestory-structure-will.html|title=Latest Skyscraper For Lower Manhattan; Thirty-one-Story Structure Will Occupy Block With Whitehall Building and Athletic Club.|date=April 17, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[Land lot|lot]] has a frontage of {{Convert|75|ft||abbr=}} on each of West and Washington Streets, and {{Convert|179|ft||abbr=}} on Morris Street, covering a total area of {{Convert|13500|ft2||abbr=}}.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe building stands on filled land along the shore of the [[North River (Hudson River)|North River]] (an archaic name for the southernmost portion of the [[Hudson River]]). The surrounding neighborhood, the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]], was the first part of Manhattan to be developed as part of [[New Netherland]] and later New York City; its population growth led city officials to add land on Manhattan's shore by filling and [[land reclamation]] in the 18th and 19th centuries.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> As the North River shoreline was deeper and had a denser concentration of buildings than the East River shoreline on the east side of Manhattan Island,<ref name=\"NYCL (DAC) p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> the land under 21 West Street was not filled until 1835, when debris from the [[Great Fire of New York]] was dumped there.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> As a result of the land filling, 21 West Street was constructed without a basement,<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-No_Basement-1930\"/> which was \"a decidedly rare feature\" in New York City buildings, hence the need to import steam and electricity.<ref name=\"NYT-No_Basement-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/12/07/archives/west-st-building-has-no-basement-steam-and-electricity-from-outside.html|title=West St. Building Has No Basement; Steam and Electricity From Outside Sources for Thirty-one Story Structure|date=December 7, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 13, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The site of 21 West Street was first occupied by small landowners who built houses in the area.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The surrounding neighborhood became a financial and shipping hub during the late 19th century;<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> as the Financial District became more densely developed, the residential landowners moved uptown and their former lands were combined to build larger commercial buildings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 75 - 21 West Street.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Facade detail showing corner windows at right]]\n\n21 West Street is 31 stories tall.{{efn|The [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] refers to the floor above ground level as the \"second story\", with the double-height ground floor considered as one story, and thus regards 21 West Street as being 31 stories tall.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The [[National Park Service]] refers to the floor above ground level as the \"third story\", considering the ground floor as the equivalent of two stories, and thus regards 21 West Street as being a 32-story building.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />}} It was designed in the [[Art Deco]] style<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> by [[Starrett & van Vleck]], who at the same time designed the adjacent Downtown Athletic Club building. Starrett & van Vleck had already designed several New York City department stores, including the [[Lord & Taylor building]], the [[Bloomingdale's|Bloomingdale's building]], and the [[Saks Fifth Avenue|Saks Fifth Avenue building]].<ref name=\"NYCL (DAC) p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=3}}</ref>\n\n=== Form ===\nThe building has a ground-story [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] which overhangs much of the Morris Street sidewalk, giving the impression that pedestrians have been transported inside the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> There are numerous [[storefront]]s beneath the arcade, as well as the entrance to the building's [[Lobby (room)|lobby]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=5}}</ref>\n\nAs mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]], the design of 21 West Street features six [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> creating the impression that the building tapers off as it ascends.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The setbacks are located on Washington Street above the 10th and 16th floors, at the northwest and northeast corners above the 21st floor, and on all sides above the 26th, 29th, and 30th floors.<ref name=\"floor-count\" group=\"lower-alpha\">In this article, the floor above ground level is referred to as the \"second floor\", even though the ground level is the equivalent of two stories. All subsequent stories are referred to using this same pattern.</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|National Park Service|1999|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL pp. 5-6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|pp=5\u20136}}</ref>\n\n=== Facade ===\nThe [[facade]] of 21 West Street was designed with molded and oversized brick \"to emphasize the structural lines and to enrich the texture of the materials\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Brick and [[architectural terracotta|terracotta]] were used in red, orange, and yellow tones,<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> a design feature influenced by [[Harvey Wiley Corbett|Harvey Wiley Corbett's]] plan for the [[Master Apartments]] in the Upper West Side of Manhattan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> For instance, the light-tan vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] highlight the building's vertical dimension, while other brick patterns give the impression of a \"skin\", including the horizontal lines of the [[spandrel]]s between the floors.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> At each setback and on the three lower levels, the [[parapet]]s have various designs of molded brick to provide [[Surface finish|surface texture]] to the building's exterior.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The southern facade is hidden behind the Downtown Athletic Club building to the south.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref>\n\nThe corners of the building were outfitted with windows wrapping around the edge at a 90-degree angle, instead of structural columns as had been provided in previous buildings, making 21 West Street possibly the first commercial building in the U.S. to have wrap-around corner windows.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Bruner1930\">{{cite journal|last=Bruner|first=Warren D.|date=June 1930|title=Office Layouts for Tenants|url=https://www.usmodernist.org/AF/AF-1930-06-2.pdf|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=52|pages=905 (PDF 67)}}</ref>{{efn|The Landmarks Preservation Commission described this as a fine distinction: the [[Master Apartments]] on the [[Upper West Side]] (built 1928\u20131929) was cited as the first ''residential'' skyscraper with corner windows,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\"/> and the Child's Restaurant building at [[604 Fifth Avenue]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]] (built 1925) was cited as the first building of any kind with such windows.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/25/realestate/25scape.html|title=The History of 3 Midtown Neighbors|last=Gray|first=Christopher|date=July 25, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 3, 2020|page=RE9||language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}} Prior to the construction of 21 West Street, corner windows had only been used on residential structures.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\n[[File:Building at 21 West Street 2013-10-14 13-21-21.jpg|thumb|Underside of one of the corners, facing the arcade on Morris Street]]\n\nDespite its address, 21 West Street's primary entrance is at the center of the Morris Street facade, beneath the one-story arcade, which includes ten [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] at ground level. Multicolored mosaics are located on the ceiling of the arcade.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> The arcade, storefronts, and main entrance contain decorative metalworks painted in silver and gold tones, which extend into the interior, described by the [[National Park Service]] as \"an unusual design feature\".<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> The piers and interior walls of the arcade are outfitted with bronze panels and lighting installations. The arcade's arches mostly consist of stepped brick, except for the fifth bay from Washington Street, which is a square marble-framed arch that leads to the main entrance. The spandrels above the arcade are textured in a chevron (V-shaped) design with tan and purple brick. The arcade continues in reduced form on the West and Washington Street facades, each being five bays wide.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />\n\nThe second floor has three windows per bay, with wrap-around windows at the corners; the second-floor<ref name=\"floor-count\" group=\"lower-alpha\" /> bays are separated by purple and tan brick piers.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> Above the ground floor, each floor of 21 West Street generally contains two rolled steel windows per bay, with wrap-around windows at the corners, each of these windows having four panes, two on each side.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> Below the setbacks on the 21st and 26th floors, the corners facing Morris Street are replaced with a single diagonal [[chamfer]]ed bay.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" />\n\n=== Features ===\nHaving constructed 21 West Street as a [[speculative development]] in anticipation of growing demand for office space in lower Manhattan,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=9}}</ref> the building's developers aimed to attract potential tenants through the unique design of the structure.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> When built, 21 West Street included high-speed elevators and other innovations \"to contribute to the comfort and convenience of its tenants\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=April 1931|title=21 West Street Office Building, New York City|url=|journal=Architecture and Building|volume=63|pages=90\u201391}}</ref> A lobby, {{Frac|1|1|2}} stories high, is located on the north side of the ground floor, linking to the two elevator banks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> The lobby has a colorful marble mosaic on its floor, depicting the old street grid of lower Manhattan in a style similar to a [[Nautical chart|mariner's map]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> There are bronze lighting installations near the elevator banks, decorated with waves and shell motifs.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\nSince its conversion to an apartment building, the interior of 21 West Street has included a [[Terrace (building)|terrace]] on the 34th floor, a play area for children, and a fitness room.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/le-rivage/|title=Le Rivage - TRD Research|date=March 13, 2019|website=The Real Deal|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The rooms were created from former office spaces; for instance, the play area was previously a [[Changing room|locker room]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Joanne|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/24/realestate/older-buildings-add-amenities-to-compete.html|title=Insert a Gym, Then a Lounge: Older Buildings Add Amenities|date=April 22, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe construction of 21 West Street occurred when the Financial District was being expanded as a commercial area. The construction of the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]]'s [[Elevated railway|elevated railroad lines]], and later the [[New York City Subway]], had spurred the relocation of the area's residential population uptown in the late 19th and early 20th centuries; the [[tenement]]s that developed at the edges of the Financial District were being demolished and replaced with office buildings.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" />\n\nThe building was owned by the 21 West Street Corporation, which had close ties with the maritime industry along the Hudson River.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> It was developed by civil engineer Alfred Rheinstein.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/05/28/archives/alfred-rheinstein-dead-at-85-founded-construction-concern-exhead-of.html|title=Alfred Rheinstein Dead at 85; Founded Construction Concern|date=May 28, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Work began on the structure in 1929,<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> the foundations had been laid by April 1930,<ref name=\":0\" /> and building work was completed in 1931.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Real estate agents William A. White & Sons were hired to rent out the space in 21 West Street.<ref name=\":0\" /> After the building's completion, the owners identified tenants in the maritime and shipping industries, including lawyers, transport companies, and import/export companies associated with the sector. In addition, naval architecture firm [[Gibbs & Cox]] was headquartered at the building for over 30 years.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Other early tenants included the Peruvian [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] in New York City,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1940/03/26/archives/peruvian-offices-to-move-uptown-consulate-for-11-years-in-21-west.html|title=Peruvian Offices To Move Uptown; Consulate, for 11 Years in 21 West St., Leases Quarters in 10 Rockefeller Plaza|date=March 26, 1940|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the Moran Towing and Transportation Company,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/12/30/archives/shipping-offices-taken-downtown-rector-and-west-street-office.html|title=Shipping Offices Taken Downtown; Rector and West Street Office Quarters Are Leased by New Tenants|date=December 30, 1943|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the Shepard Steamship Company,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1947/02/10/archives/shepard-offices-moved-steamship-company-gets-new-quarters-at-21.html|title=Shepard Offices Moved; Steamship Company Gets New Quarters at 21 West Street|date=February 10, 1947|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the Hedger Transportation Corporation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/10/22/archives/financial-firms-moving-three-lease-in-21-west-street-and-goldman.html|title=Financial Firms Moving; Three Lease in 21 West Street and Goldman Sachs Building|date=October 22, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Around 1950, the main entrance was modified and a [[heating, ventilation, and air conditioning]] system was installed.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, the residential development and management firm, Rose Associates, announced plans to convert 21 West Street into a 293-unit apartment building called Le Rivage. It was to be the firm's first project in 10 years and its first Manhattan project below [[8th Street and St. Mark's Place|8th Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Garbarine|first=Rachelle|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/11/nyregion/rose-associates-enters-the-conversion-market.html|title=Rose Associates Enters The Conversion Market|date=July 11, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was designated a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1998,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> and was listed on the National Park Service's [[National Register of Historic Places]] the following year,<ref name=\"NPS p. 1\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|1999|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> at which time it was recorded in the register that 21 West Street had been \"abandoned for over a decade\".<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> When the building was damaged in [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, residents' rents were temporarily lowered.<ref name=\"The Real Deal 2019\" /> The residential units in 21 West Street were partially renovated in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/10/realestate/the-financial-district-gains-momentum.html|title=The Financial District Gains Momentum|date=August 8, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal box|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[Art Deco architecture of New York City]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1999.pdf|title=21 West Street Building|date=June 16, 1998|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1998}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2075.pdf|title=Downtown Athletic Club Building|date=November 14, 2000|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/99000316.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Building at 21 West Street|date=February 11, 1999|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|1999}}}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|21 West Street}}\n* {{official|http://www.21west.com}}\n* [http://www.rosenyc.com/rentals/21-west-street/ Rose Associates, Inc. - Building Management Company Site]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n{{New York City Historic Sites}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Art Deco architecture in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:West Side Highway]]\n", "name_user": "Rodney Baggins", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFacad